00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:17.550
As the result sank in, her two Russian teammates

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:19.200
earned gold and silver.

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:20.940
The bronze went to Japan.

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:22.680
Valieva finished fourth.

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:25.500
It was very heartbreaking to watch this

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.120
unfold the way that it did.

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:28.620
You couldn't help but feel empathy

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:31.230
for her and for the situation that she's been put in

00:12:31.230 --> 00:12:33.210
as a 15-year-old, as a child.

00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:36.810
Valieva tested positive for a banned substance last December

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:40.020
but was cleared to compete while her case is reviewed.

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:42.990
Unfortunately, the longevity of figure skaters,

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:46.170
and particularly Russian figure skaters, is two to three years.

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:48.330
I don't think she's back for the next Olympics.

00:12:48.330 --> 00:12:52.350
Team Canada wins their fifith gold medal in women's hockey.

00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:54.690
As for Team USA the women's hockey team

00:12:54.690 --> 00:12:58.680
was denied back-to-back gold medals, losing in the finals

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:02.730
to their rival Canada for the fourth time in Olympic history.

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:08.210
But star forward Hilary Knight vowed, "we'll be back."

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.290
Mikaela Shiffrin will also be back.

00:13:10.290 --> 00:13:12.230
She decided to race one more time

00:13:12.230 --> 00:13:14.330
in a record-tying sixth event today

00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:16.250
in hopes of medalling at these games.

00:13:16.250 --> 00:13:17.900
While the quirky group of US men's

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:21.860
curlers who won gold in 2018 will now play for bronze

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:23.450
against Canada later today.

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:24.530
Norah.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:26.960
Quirky is good, and it looks really cold there in Beijing.

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:28.760
Jamie Yuccas, thanks.

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:30.230
It is.

00:13:30.230 --> 00:13:31.850
Well, now to the Mississippi Delta,

00:13:31.850 --> 00:13:33.680
one of the poorest regions and the poorest

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:34.910
state in the nation.

00:13:34.910 --> 00:13:36.740
CBS's Janet Shamlian traveled there

00:13:36.740 --> 00:13:39.080
for tonight's Eye on America to spotlight

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:41.870
a program that's trying to bring change one

00:13:41.870 --> 00:13:44.350
storefront at a time.

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.270
Hi, Ms. Maggie.

00:13:46.270 --> 00:13:50.770
It's a dream come true for Kenesha Lewis,

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:53.870
her own smoothie shop, Kay's Kute Fruit, in Greenville,

00:13:53.870 --> 00:13:54.640
Mississippi.

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:56.920
She used to sell them from her apartment.

00:13:56.920 --> 00:13:59.980
Oh, we bought this place.

00:13:59.980 --> 00:14:00.820
How does that feel?

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:01.590
It's awesome.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.230
Like what?

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:02.730
Me?

00:14:02.730 --> 00:14:04.570
Awesome, we really, really bought it?

00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:05.800
Yeah, we bought it.

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:08.260
Black-owned businesses are a minority in the Mississippi

00:14:08.260 --> 00:14:12.670
Delta even with the population in some places more than 70%

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:13.960
African-American.

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:16.300
In a state with the nation's highest poverty

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:20.950
rate, almost 20% in parts of the Delta, it's more than double

00:14:20.950 --> 00:14:21.610
that.

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:24.520
Majority of the businesses I was seeing sustaining

00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:28.310
were White-owned and the math just didn't add up to me.

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:31.240
And so I figured that there was a resource gap.

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:33.250
Tim Lampkin wanted to close that gap

00:14:33.250 --> 00:14:35.170
and help business owners like Lewis

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:37.570
who had trouble getting a loan.

00:14:37.570 --> 00:14:40.090
He saw the region increasingly distressed

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:43.540
and the wealth gap growing when he quit a big city job

00:14:43.540 --> 00:14:45.640
to return to his Delta home.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.280
When you came back here and you realized what was happening,

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:49.450
what did you think?

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:51.310
The first thing I thought was how

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:54.160
am I going to be a part of the solution.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.950
I never think about things from a deficit mindset,

00:14:56.950 --> 00:14:59.260
it's always optimistic.

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:03.190
Tim started Higher Purpose to provide mentors and connect

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:07.090
lenders to people like nurse practitioner Mary Williams.

00:15:07.090 --> 00:15:10.130
It's the only half the dose of your first shot.

00:15:10.130 --> 00:15:10.630
OK.

00:15:10.630 --> 00:15:12.790
She saw the need for an emergency care center

00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:15.820
in Clarksdale, the closest was 45 minutes away.

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:19.450
But says, even with seed money, banks turned her down.

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:24.130
My proposal may be the exact same as my White counterparts'

00:15:24.130 --> 00:15:27.790
proposal but yet it doesn't carry the same weight

00:15:27.790 --> 00:15:28.870
to the lender.

00:15:28.870 --> 00:15:30.160
OK, come on.

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:33.400
Higher Purpose introduced her to a lender who made the loan.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:36.880
The clinic has become a lifeline beyond health care.

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:38.980
When you help someone like Dr. Williams,

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:41.060
what's the impact on the community?

00:15:41.060 --> 00:15:44.020
It's really important that people see themselves

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:45.050
in their community.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:48.670
And so this is much bigger than myself or Dr. Williams.

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:53.350
It's more about creating a new legacy and generation.

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:56.170
A generation of business-owners reflective

00:15:56.170 --> 00:15:57.820
of the community they serve.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:15:59.170
I mentor young ladies.

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:02.200
And to know that they watch me, they're understanding things,

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:04.240
they're coming out of their shells with things,

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:06.430
that makes my heart healthy because I'm

00:16:06.430 --> 00:16:07.690
walking in my purpose.

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:10.800
Leveling the playing field after decades of disparity.

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:11.490
See you later.

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:12.160
Have a good one.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:14.410
For Eye on America, Janet Shamlian

00:16:14.410 --> 00:16:16.930
in the Mississippi Delta.

00:16:16.930 --> 00:16:18.220
Such a great program.

